mpanion essay from scientist and former congressman Rush Holt, offering a brief introduction and consideration of what society needs most from science now. Reflecting on the report’s legacy and relevance along with its limitations, Holt’s essay contends that the public’s ability to cope with today’s issues—such as public health, the changing climate and environment, and challenging technologies in modern society—requires a more capacious understanding of what science can contribute. Holt considers how scientists should think of their obligation to society and what the public should demand from science, and he calls for a renewed understanding of science’s value for democracy and society at large.A touchstone for concerned citizens, scientists, and policymakers, Science, the Endless Frontier endures as a passionate articulation of the power and potential of science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aResearchzUnited States. 0aResearch-United States. 0aScience and statezUnited States. 0aScience and state-United States. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAmerican Association for the Advancement of Science.  aAnthony Fauci.  aBeyond Sputnik.  aDeborah Birx.  aFrance Cordova.  aHarry Truman.  aKilgore.  aNational Science Foundation.  aNavigating the Maze.  aQanon.  aScience in society.  aThe Death of Truth.  aTruth Decay.  aUnion of Concerned Scientists.  aanti-vaxxer.  abasic science research.  aclinical trials.  adeath of expertise.  aevidence-based thinking.  ascience and democracy.  ascience and the citizen.  ascience and the public.  ascience budget.  ascientific evidence.  ascientific thinking.  ascientific truth.  avaccines.  awhy teach science.  awhy trust science.1 aBush, Vannevar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r